    "7557896": {
      "title": "Power ratio estimation in incoherent backscatter lidar: direct detection with Gaussisn noise",
      "abstract": "Properties of small sample estimators for the return signal power ratio or log ratio in direct detection incoherent backscatter lidar systems are analyzed. As for heterodyne receivers it is usually preferable to form an estimator from the logarithmic difference of the sample averages rather than their ratio. Calculated values of bias and noise figures are confirmed using simulated data based on constant signal models and compared with the estimates obtained from nonlinear Kalman filters. The latter generally provide the least bias at high noise levels at the cost of greater computational complexity."
    },
    "121273737": {
      "title": "Image restoration using reduced order models",
      "abstract": "Abstract The one-dimensional state-space representation of an image for restoration using a Kalman filter requires a relatively large state vector. For a typical autoregressive signal model with nonsymmetric half-plane support, the dimension of the state is approximately equal to the product of the image model order and the pixel width of the image. This state is quite large particularly for practical applications and would require excessive computation if the Kalman filter were used directly. Consequently, there have been varying filtering approximations which reduce this computation. An alternative approach, presented here, is the reduction of the dimension of the state representation by approximation and the use of the corresponding optimal filter directly. To this effect a reduced order model Kalman filter (ROMKF) which reduces both the quantity and the complexity of the computations is developed. This ROMKF should prove to be particularly advantageous for adaptive filtering of images due to the low state dimensionality."
    }
  },
